      "title": "Digit Snakes",
      "topics": [],
      "fastest": true,
      "reverse": true,
      "shortest": false,
      "solution": "import sys\nimport math\n\nn = input()\nc = int(input())\n\n# Below is the actual solution:\ns = \"\"\na = []\nfor i in range(min(len(n), c)):\n  s += n[i]\n  if (i+1) % 8 == 0:\n    if len(a) % 2 > 0:\n      a.append(s[::-1])\n    else:\n      a.append(s)\n    s = \"\"\nif s>\"\":\n  while len(s) < 8:\n    s += \"X\"\n  if len(a) % 2 > 0:\n    a.append(s[::-1])\n  else:\n    a.append(s)\nfor i in a:\n  print(i)",
      "statement": "Time to make a digit snake! You are given a string [[n]] made of digits {{0-9}} and an integer [[c]].\n\n<<Steps:>>\n<<1)>> Take the first [[c]] digits of the string [[n]]. If [[c]] calls for too many digits (i.e. [[c]] > length of [[n]]), then just use the digits from [[n]] only.\n<<2)>> Split that substring into chunks of {{8}} digits. \n<<3)>> If the last chunk has less than {{8}} characters, fill in the gaps with {{X}}'s until the last chunk is {{8}} digits long.\n<<4)>> Print each chunk on a new line. Keep chunks at even indices {{(0, 2, 4, ...)}} as they are, but reverse chunks at odd indices {{(1, 3, 5, ...)}}.\n\n<<Example:>>\n[[n]] = {{1234567890987654321234567890}}\n[[c]] = {{20}}\n<<1)>> First [[c]] digits of [[n]]: {{12345678909876543212}}\n<<2)>> Split substring into chunks of {{8}}:\n<<Chunk 0:>> {{12345678}}\n<<Chunk 1:>> {{90987654}}\n<<Chunk 2:>> {{3212}}\n<<3)>> Fill in the last chunk with {{X}}'s: {{3212XXXX}}\n<<4)>> Print each chunk and reverse chunks at odd indices:\n<<Line 1:>> {{12345678}} <<(keep)>>\n<<Line 2:>> {{45678909}} <<(reverse)>>\n<<Line 3:>> {{3212XXXX}} <<(keep)>>\n\nGood luck!",
